1) Cron expression field layout and allowed values
- Standard (Vixie) five-field: minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week. Field positions and numeric ranges:
  minute: 0-59
  hour: 0-23
  day-of-month: 1-31
  month: 1-12 or JAN-DEC
  day-of-week: 0-6 (Sunday=0) or names SUN-SAT; some systems accept 7 as Sunday
- Six-/seven-field variants (Quartz-style, cron-parser): include seconds as leading field and optionally year as trailing field.
  seconds: 0-59
  year (optional): 1970-2099 (implementation-dependent)
- System crontabs sometimes accept an extra user field after time fields (system crontab only).

2) Special characters and exact semantics
- * : wildcard equals "every" value in that field.
- , : list separator, enumerates distinct values.
- - : range inclusive, e.g., 1-5 includes endpoints.
- / : step/increment. "A/B" means start at A then every B units; "*/B" equals "0/B" for numeric fields.
- ? : in Quartz and some implementations used as "no specific value" and is allowed only in day-of-month or day-of-week to resolve ambiguity. Functionally treated as unspecified for matching rules.
- L : "last" semantics. In day-of-month = last day of month. In day-of-week with a trailing value (e.g., 5L) = last weekday X of month. L may accept offsets (L-3) in Quartz.
- W : nearest weekday to specified day-of-month. If target falls on Sat/Sun, shifts to Fri/Mon with constraints (won't cross month boundary).
- # : day-of-week#n selects the n-th occurrence of the weekday that month (e.g., 6#3 = third Friday). If nth occurrence doesn't exist that month, no firing for that spec.
- % : percent signs in the command part are converted to newline characters; must be escaped with backslash to preserve literal % in command arguments (system behavior for cron command parsing).
- H : special hashed/jitter value (cron-parser/Jenkins style). 'H' resolves to a deterministic pseudo-random value within the field's permitted range. Seeded via hashSeed.

3) Five-, six- and seven-field variants and cross-implementation differences
- POSIX/Vixie standard: five-field expression maps to minute..day-of-week; some systems extend to six fields by adding seconds or username depending on context (system crontab). Amazon EventBridge uses 1-7 for day-of-week.
- Quartz: requires seconds field (six- or seven-field). Quartz accepts named months and weekdays and offers L, W, ?, #, /, -, , semantics and allows year field.
- Interoperability rule: explicitly map your engine's expected field count and semantics before parsing (e.g., cron-parser supports seconds optional and strict mode that enforces 6 fields).

4) Day-of-month vs Day-of-week interaction rules
- Traditional cron: if both day-of-month and day-of-week are restricted (not *), the job runs when either field matches; implementations differ — some require both match. Use explicit semantics or strict mode to avoid ambiguity.
- Quartz: requires using '?' in one of the two fields to indicate "no specific value" when the other is used; '?' prevents ambiguous matching.

5) Quartz-specific behavior and semantics
- Field order: seconds minutes hours day-of-month month day-of-week [year].
- Allowed specials: ?, L, W, #, /, -, , and *.
- L in day-of-week: numericL (e.g., 6L) means last occurrence of that weekday in the month.
- W: nearest weekday to a given day-of-month; cannot be used with ranges/lists.
- # : nth weekday-of-month (e.g., 2#1 = first Monday).
- Year is optional and expected in range 1970-2099 in Quartz docs.

6) cron-parser (harrisiirak/cron-parser) API and options (concrete signatures and behaviors)
- Primary parse method: CronExpressionParser.parse(expression, options?) -> CronExpressionInterval
  Options (object):
    currentDate: Date | string | number — if omitted and startDate exists, startDate is used; default is current local time in UTC.
    startDate: Date | string | number — sets iteration lower bound; used as fallback for currentDate.
    endDate: Date | string | number — sets iteration upper bound; iteration.next() throws if beyond endDate.
    tz: string — IANA timezone identifier, e.g., Europe/London. When provided, parser uses Luxon to calculate dates in that tz and handles DST transitions.
    hashSeed: string — seed used for H hashed special character deterministic jitter.
    strict: boolean — enable strict validation: requires full 6-field expression, forbids simultaneous day-of-month and day-of-week, rejects empty expression defaults.
    tz-aware behavior: when tz is set, all returned Date objects represent times in that tz context; iteration and DST boundary handling are correct (no duplicated or skipped local times).
- Returned CronExpressionInterval implements iterator protocol and provides methods:
    next() -> Date  (returns next occurrence or throws when endDate exceeded)
    prev() -> Date  (returns previous occurrence)
    take(n: number) -> Date[]  (collect next n occurrences)
    stringify() -> string (returns normalized expression string with resolved H values when deterministic)
- CronFileParser.parseFile(path) -> Promise<{variables: Record, expressions: Array, errors: Array}> (async)
- CronFileParser.parseFileSync(path) -> {variables, expressions, errors}
- CronFieldCollection.from(fields, overrides) -> CronFieldCollection instance; overrides accept raw arrays or CronField instances. CronFieldCollection.stringify() returns expression string.

7) Timezone and DST handling (IANA tzdb and Intl)
- Use IANA timezone names (Europe/London, America/New_York) when specifying tz in cron parsing and iterations. IANA tzdb is authoritative and periodically updated; use data distributions (tzdata) and keep them current.
- IANA tzdb distribution files: tzdata2026a (data), tzdb-2026a.tar.lz, tzcode2026a.tar.gz. Fetch via IANA HTTP/FTP/rsync endpoints.
- DST edge cases: when firing times fall into DST transitions, engines must choose one behavior explicitly: skip nonexistent local times (spring forward) or return repeated times (fall back) with offset disambiguation.
- In JS runtimes, use Intl and a timezone-aware library (e.g., Luxon) for canonical timezone handling and formatting; Intl.DateTimeFormat and Intl.getCanonicalLocales help with locale negotiation and canonicalization but do not substitute for tzdb for historical offsets.

8) Predefined macros and non-standard directives
- Common macros: @yearly/@annually -> 0 0 1 1 *, @monthly -> 0 0 1 * *, @weekly -> 0 0 * * 0, @daily/@midnight -> 0 0 * * *, @hourly -> 0 * * * *, @reboot -> run once on daemon start (non-deterministic across implementations).
- cron-parser defines additional predefs: @minutely, @secondly, @weekdays, @weekends and maps them to explicit expanded field patterns.

9) Jitter (H) and deterministic seeding
- 'H' replaces a field value with a deterministic pseudo-random number within that field's allowed range. Use hashSeed option to consistently derive the same H at parse time across runs for stable schedules.
- Syntax variants supported: H, H(range), H/step, H(range)/step (cron-parser supports these patterns). The random offset respects step constraints: offset < step.

10) Crontab file parsing and variables
- CronFileParser extracts variables and expressions from typical crontab files, returns variables map, expressions array with parsed CronExpressionInterval objects (or parse errors), and errors list for diagnostics.
- Percent conversion: unescaped '%' characters in command section are treated as newline markers by most cron implementations; CronFileParser should implement the same parsing rules.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS (implementation and configuration specifics)

A. Field numeric mapping and aliases
- Month names: JAN=1, FEB=2, ..., DEC=12 (case-insensitive). Implement mapping table for both full names and three-letter abbreviations.
- Day-of-week names: SUN=0 or 7 (both accepted by many libs), MON=1 ... SAT=6. Normalize to numeric internals; prefer 0=Sunday internal representation but accept 7 as alias for Sunday.

B. Strict validation rules (recommended engine defaults)
- Enable strict mode by default for server-side validation of user expressions if ambiguity is unacceptable. Strict rules:
  - Require 6 fields when seconds are expected; otherwise accept and internally normalize.
  - Disallow specifying both day-of-month and day-of-week unless explicit '?' present.
  - Validate ranges and characters; reject unknown month/day names.

C. Timezone resolution and library choices
- Use IANA tzdb names; for JS use Luxon (DateTime.fromISO(..., { zone })). Ensure your runtime's tzdb is current; either vendor tzdb with your app or rely on system tzdata but document update procedures.
- For canonicalization of locale or timezone strings, use Intl.getCanonicalLocales for locales and maintain mapping table for common timezone aliases (e.g., UTC, GMT).

D. DST behavior policy (engine must choose and document one)
- Option 1: Interpret schedule in local wall-clock time; on spring-forward missing local times are skipped; on fall-back repeated local times produce two occurrences with distinct absolute timestamps. Use timezone-aware library to compute next occurrences robustly.
- Option 2: Interpret schedule in absolute UTC time adjusted for timezone offsets; not recommended for user-facing local schedule semantics.

